Claude.md:  Coding conventions and other pointers
    -There is a hierarcy library contains many modules which contain many classes.
        The compiler will enforce no cyclic dependencies between modules.
        The linker will enforce no cyclic dependencies between libraries.
        Cyclic dependencies between tightly coupled classes within one module is allowed.
    -Only re-export modules that don't internal in name .Internal. The goal is to avoid importing anything internal accross library boundaries.
    -The only header in project if forward.H and it is used to forward declare unit test classes the need access
     to internals of certain library classes.
    -Use CamelBack for names, but surround acronyms with under scores like HF_Evaluator, or HF_DFT_Evaluator
    -I make liberal use of abstract interface base classes with no data (default constructors).  These are
    always derived from with virtual inheritance.  This makes lots of diamonds in the tree, but they should be harmless diamonds.
    Some OOP people are surprised by this.




